         <ref id="ref1">
            <label>1.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">As David Hume wrote of his<source>
                  <italic>Treatise</italic>
               </source>(<year>1955</year>,<fpage>4</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref2">
            <label>2.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Here, I am primarily interested in the reception from English and American philosophers. But we should not forget the extent of Perelman's recognition by philosophers on the continent, seen variously in such things as his contribution to the festschrift for Gadamer's seventieth birthday (<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Bubner</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <year>1970</year>) and<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Ricoeur</string-name>
               </person-group>'s (<year>2000</year>) interest in the universal audience.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref3">
            <label>3.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Although some commentators in fact see Frege as a candidate for the title of “father” of ordinary language philosophy (<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Chapman</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <year>2005</year>,<fpage>34</fpage>), one must recall Frege's efforts to produce a formalized language of pure thought (see<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Frege</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <year>1979</year>,<fpage>252</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref4">
            <label>4.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Much of this discussion of the Oxford group is drawn from Siobhan Chapman's biography of<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Paul Grice</string-name>
               </person-group>(<year>2005</year>). Another thread of interest in ordinary language philosophy would be traced to Cambridge and the group around Wittgenstein (see<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Hanfling</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <year>2000</year>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref5">
            <label>5.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Grice admits that ordinary language philosophy is hard to categorize and that it has been approached in different ways by various philosophers within the group (<year>1989</year>,<fpage>171</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref6">
            <label>6.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">We find it, for example, in the “parent” text of<source>
                  <italic>The New Rhetoric</italic>
               </source>(<year>1969</year>,<fpage>112</fpage>–<lpage>14</lpage>) as well as in the popularizing discussions of<source>
                  <italic>The Realm of Rhetoric</italic>
               </source>(<year>1982</year>,<fpage>22</fpage>–<lpage>24</lpage>) and in<article-title>“The New Rhetoric”</article-title>(<year>1971</year>), the text to which Mackie is referring. Note, though, that not all versions of the papers that bear this title include discussions of the petitio principii, Perelman 1963 being a case in point.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref7">
            <label>7.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">This without fully endorsing the concept, the shortcomings of which he has discussed elsewhere (<year>1961</year>,<fpage>155</fpage>), where he credited Perelman with formulating one of the best modern expressions of the idea of justice. Still, we might imagine that Perelman's work had an influence on Hart's writing between the 1961<italic>Concept of Law</italic>and his presentation of Perelman's ideas in his introduction to the 1963<italic>Idea of Justice and the Problem of Argument</italic>.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref8">
            <label>8.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">My intention here is not to give a full treatment of Johnstone's constructive engagement with Perelman's ideas (which would command far more space than is available) but only to draw on some of its most salient features, ones that have relevance for the discussion later.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref9">
            <label>9.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">As I will suggest, this is a more interesting problem than has been allowed, since it means that two senses of validity are at work in audiences. Of course, in advocating a logic of argumentation, Perelman never suggested that the principles of demonstrative reasoning would cease to be operative.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref10">
            <label>10.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">According to the proceedings of the conference (Cahiers de Royaumont 1962), papers were presented by Leslie Beck, Jean Wahl, J. O. Urmson, Bernard Williams, Gilbert Ryle, Peter Strawson, Willard V. O. Quine, Leo Apostel, Evert W. Beth, J. L. Austin and R. M. Hare. Other attendees took part in the discussions, and this group included Perelman, as well as A. J. Ayer, Patrick Nowell-Smith, and Maurice Merleau-Ponty.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref11">
            <label>11.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">For a fuller discussion of the process of dissociation whereby term 2 is drawn from term 1 see Perelman and Olbrechts-Tyteca 1969, 416ff., and Perelman 1982,<fpage>126</fpage>–<lpage>37</lpage>.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref12">
            <label>12.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">
               <article-title>“There can only be adherence to this idea of excluding individuals from the human community if the number and intellectual value of those banned are not so high as to make such a procedure ridiculous”</article-title>(<year>1969</year>,<fpage>33</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref13">
            <label>13.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">For a much fuller interpretation of the universal audience as the concept is used by Perelman, see my 2006 and 2004, chap. 6.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref14">
            <label>14.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">In all models of argumentation, the status of basic premises and what justifies them as basic is a significant problem. For a discussion of this in informal logic, for example, see Freeman 2005.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref15">
            <label>15.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Goodwin sees an essential problem in Perelman's account: he wants to show a relationship between adherence and conviction that could characterize philosophical discourse, but, suggests Goodwin, philosophers seem not to be aiming at instilling convictions in anyone. I suspect this is indeed the kind of dissonance that has prevented philosophers generally from taking up Perelman's ideas. But the problem lies not in Perelman's account, as I attempt to show, but in the understanding of it.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref16">
            <label>16.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">
               <article-title>“Thus each argument exhibits stages, marked out by the agreements that should be reached”</article-title>(<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Perelman</string-name>
               </person-group>and<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Olbrechts-Tyteca</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <year>1969</year>,<fpage>110</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref17">
            <label>17.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Thus, I do not agree with Goodwin's claim that convictions are not reducible to strong adherences (<year>1995</year>,<fpage>223</fpage>). On the other hand, her point that Perelman's account lacks the richness that would discriminate between the treatments involved for different levels of adherence remains a problem to be addressed elsewhere.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref18">
            <label>18.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">This is a philosophical problem in Perelman's account but not one we can pursue here. The intentions of an agent are hidden from public view, so suggesting, for example, that the audience for an argument is that which the arguer<italic>intended</italic>to influence is clearly problematic. A possible solution lies in the degree to which the audience comes into play in deciding what an arguer intends (<person-group person-group-type="author">
                  <string-name>Perelman</string-name>
               </person-group>
               <year>1982</year>,<fpage>90</fpage>).</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref19">
            <label>19.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">Consider, for example, the obstacles and sacrifices that have to be made in some parts of the world by people who have been persuaded that they should go out and vote.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
         <ref id="ref20">
            <label>20.</label>
            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">It might also condemn us to the pessimism I mentioned in the introduction of this paper, since on the measure of effectiveness alone, the new rhetoric project has not (yet) persuaded its principal audience.</mixed-citation>
         </ref>
